photo.description: Woodcut llustration of a well-dressed humanoid figure with the eyes of a lynx, the ears of a pig, the neck of a swan or snake, and the right foot of a bear. A lion's head is on its breast; from its mouth protrude a sword and a spray of lily leaves. The figure holds a closed purse in its right hand and is dropping coins from its left. The woodcut is by Hans Sebald Beham. For analysis, see M. Curschmann, "Facies peccatorum -- Vir bonus: Bild-Text-Formeln zwischen Hochmittelalter und früher Neuzeit" in Poesis et Pictura, ed. S. Füssel and J. Knape (Baden-Baden: V. Koerner, 1989), p. 157-189. Used by Christian Egenolff of Frankfurt am Main. photo.description: Woodcut illustration of Grammar as a memory image from Johann Horst von Romberch's work on memory, Congestorium artificiose memorie (Venice: Melchiorre Sessa, 1533). "This is one of the very rare cases in which memory image is illustrated; and the image turns out to be the familiar figure of old Grammatica, the first of the liberal arts, with some of her familiar attributes, the scalpel and the ladder. She is here not only the well-known personification of the liberal art of Grammar, but a memory image being used to remember material about grammar through inscriptions on her. The inscription across her chest and the images near or on her are derived from Romberch's visual alphabets, both the 'objects' ones and the 'birds' one which he is using in combination."--F.A. Yates, The Art of Memory (London: Pimlico, 1992), p. 126. Established heading: Sessa, Melchiorre,‏ ‎‡d fl. 1506-1549‏ Penn Libraries call number: GC5 H7958 520c 1533 All images from this book

photo.description: Woodcut diagram of a portion of a visual alphabet and its application from Johann Horst von Romberch's work on memory, Congestorium artificiose memorie (Venice: Melchiorre Sessa, 1533). "Visual alphabets are ways of representing letters of the alphabet by images. These are formed in various ways; for example with pictures of objects whose shape resemble [sic] letters of the alphabet, as compasses or a ladder for A; or a hoe for N. Another way is through pictures of animals or birds arranged in the order of the first letter of their names, as A for Anser, goose, B for Bubo, owl."--F.A. Yates, The Art of Memory (London: Pimlico, 1992), p. 124-125. Established heading: Sessa, Melchiorre,‏ ‎‡d fl. 1506-1549‏ Penn Libraries call number: GC5 H7958 520c 1533 All images from this book

photo.description: Woodcut explicating the abbey memory system of the Dominican Johann Horst von Romberch in his Congestorium artificiose memorie (Venice: Melchiorre Sessa, 1533). In this cut are "sets of objects to be memorized in the courtyard, library, and chapel of the abbey. Each fifth place is marked with a hand and each tenth place with a cross, in accordance with the instructions given in [the popular rhetorical textbook] Ad Herennium for distinguishing the fifth and tenth places. Obviously there is an association here with the five fingers. As Memory moved along the places, these were ticked off on the fingers."--F.A. Yates, The Art of Memory (London: Pimlico, 1992), p. 116. photo.description: Described in The Library Chronicle of the Friends of the University of Pennsylvania Library XXVI (1961), p. 84, as "a thirty-two line Latin poem in manuscript addressed to Cardinal Alessandro Farnese" by the "enigmatic" M. Spi., author of the printed text to which this ms. has been added. The poem appears to honor (or at least to mention repeatedly) Pope Julius III (1487-1555; papacy 1550-1555), born Giovanni Maria Ciocchi del Monte. He succeeded Pope Paul III (1468-1549; papacy 1534-1549), also born Alessandro Farnese. The poem's dedicatee, Paul III's grandson Alessandro Cardinal Farnese, was a power broker in the conclave which elected Julius III as a compromise candidate. photo.description: Basilij Zanchij ad Io chrysostomu[m] fratrem Dum frater german[...] [...]s chrysostom[...] chartis Cenomanu[m] gentes texis et orobies Dum titulos, dum facta refers, dum C[a]esaris arma, Parta[que] pugnaci veg[...] superba manu Qua cynips[?] Libyea arua[?] vigas, qua culta Tune[...] Cornigero fuma[n]t qua sua [...]ura Ioui[?] Dum Patriam scriptis celebras, tibi gloria surgit Clara [...]uc est ipso C[a]esari fama minor. [Laudatory verse by Basilio Zanchi (1501-ca. 1558) for his brother Giovanni Crisostomo Zanchi (d. 1566). Both brothers joined the Canons Regular of the Lateran. Basilio was a poet and protege of Leo X; unfortunately, he fell foul of Paul IV for refusing to remain in his monastery and was imprisoned in Rome in 1558. He is supposed to have died there. Giovanni Crisostomo outlived him and indeed rose to become head of their order in 1559. His historical work De Orobiorum seu Cenomanorum Origine Libri Tres is praised in this poem.] Established heading: Zanchi, Basilio, ǂd 1501-ca. 1558 Penn Libraries call number: IC5 Za158 536p All images from this book
photo.title: Laudatory verse by Basilio Zanchi (1501-ca. 1558) for his brother Giovanni Crisostomo Zanchi (d. 1566)

photo.description: Anno d[omi]nj mil[lesim]o cccco s[e]xig[esim]o [sic?] nono declaratum est in consilio basiliensi beatissim{am?} vi[r]gine[m?] nu[m]q[uam] subiacuisse peccato originali quod semper [...] verum[?] l[...] [...] [...] co[n]silij determinatione[m?] plures aliter [...] [...] processu semp[...] quod[?] se[m]per suis [...] [...] resolutione co[n]clusum est spiritu[?] [...] [...] [The first hand is probably recording the approbation of the Doctrine of the Immaculate Conception by the Council of Basel on 18 December 1439. ("AD 1469" in line one is probably an error for "1439" because the Council of Basel ran from 1431-1445.) This approbation never "took" in the church at large because the Council's authoritative status was undermined by its subsequent deposition of Pope Eugene IV and appointment of the anti-pope Felix V. The doctrine wasn't formally promulgated as dogma until 1854, though the Council of Basel's statement on the matter was often used to support it.] Penn Libraries call number: IC5 T5988 524l All images from this book
photo.title: Ms. inscription recording the approbation of the Doctrine of the Immaculate Conception by the Council of Basel on 18 December 1439.

photo.description: Woodcut coat of arms of the House of Wittelsbach (the arms of Palatinate quartered with those of Bavaria (Wittelsbach)): The Golden Lion represents the administrative region of Upper Palatinate. The inescutcheon of white and blue fusils askance was originally the coat of arms of the Counts of Bogen, adopted in 1247 by the House of Wittelsbach. The white-and-blue fusils are indisputably the emblem of Bavaria and these arms today symbolize Bavaria as a whole. The dedication reads: "Illustrissimo principi, ac Domino, Domino Alberto, Comiti Palatino Rheni, superioris, inferioris que Bavariae Duci. Domino suo clementissimo. Osvaldus ab Eck S.D." At the time this book was published (1541), there were two concurrent Dukes of Bavaria, older brother William (i.e. Wilhelm) IV of Bavaria (1493-1550), Duke of Bavaria from 1508 to 1550, and until 1545 together with his younger brother Louis (i.e. Ludwig) X, Duke of Bavaria. Both sons of Albert IV, Duke of Bavaria. All of these were members of the House of Wittelsbach, and presumably the double helm & crest indicate the concurrent Dukes. Penn Libraries call number: FC G2393 541a Catalog record All images from this book

photo.description: George G. Kennaway - From His Mother. April 1855. Probably George Glass Kennaway (ca. 1824-1868?) of Hoopern House, Exeter, Devon, UK, son of the Exeter solicitor and liberal politician Mark Kennaway and his wife Harriet (née Codrington). George matriculated at Christ Church College, Oxford, in 1842 at age 18 and took his BA in 1846 and his MA in 1848; cf. J. Foster, Alumni Oxonienses (Oxford: Parker & Co., 1888), v. 2, p. 786. He contributed to the restoration of Wynard's Chapel (also called Trinity Chapel, but not to be confused with the nearby Holy Trinity Church) in Exeter, where he is buried. According to B. Cresswell, Exeter Churches (Exeter: J.G. Commin, 1908) p. 61, his epitaph reads: Here lieth George Glass Kennaway, of Christchurch, Oxon. Eldest son of Mark Kennaway of Hoopern Esqr., by Harriet Codrington second daughter of George Daniel of this city. A cheerful restorer of this ancient chapel and Gods House, a liberal benefactor to the pries [sic] and the poor. He deceased Dec. xxxi mdccclxvii in the xlvi year of his age. For "mdccclxvii" read "1868," I think, judging from the fact that his death at age 45 (the 46th year of his age) was registered in early 1869; cf. information transcribed by FreeBMD from the civil registration index of births, marriages and deaths for England and Wales. Harvard Library MS Eng 898 ("Sonnets, and Poems, written by John Bampfylde Esqr.") evidently has Kennaways ownership inscription, dated 1863 at Hoopern House. Cf. C.R. Woodring, "Charles Lamb in the Harvard Library" in Harvard Library Bulletin 10.2 (1956), p. 210, n. 5. For his mother, Harriet Codrington Kennaway (d. 1861), see her obituary notice in The London Review 3 (1861), p. 332. Penn Libraries call number: EC8 T3257 853e All images from this book
photo.title: Inscription to George Glass Kennaway (ca. 1824-1868?)

photo.description: Beginning of the letter in this envelope Envelope addressed to "Elder Esq[ui]re care of Messrs. Smith, Elder & Co. 65 Cornhill London" with cancelled penny red stamp (issued from 1841-1879) in upper right corner. Smith, Elder & Co. was a notable 19th-century British publishing firm founded by George Smith (1789-1846) -- later succeeded by his son, George Murray Smith (1824-1901) -- and Alexander Elder (1790-1876). The firm took up residence at 65 Cornhill in 1824 and remained there until 1868, when it moved to Waterloo Place. Cf. George Murray Smith's entry in the ODNB. Per the letter's signature, the hand is that of "Erskine Neale" -- probably Erskine Neale (1804–1883), Anglican clergyman and author, whose work The Life-Book of a Labourer was published by Smith, Elder & Co. in 1839. Established heading: Smith, Elder, and Co. Established heading: Neale, Erskine, 1804-1883. Penn Libraries call number: EC8 N2555 839l Catalog record All images from this book
photo.title: Envelope addressed to Alexander Elder (1790-1876) from Erskine Neale (1804-1883)

The result has been to shake my confidence in the party; therefore I write not to trouble you with any representation to Sir John Pirie on his Right-hand column: behalf. But I nevertheless beg again to express my thanks to you for your kind reception of my request. Yrs. dear Sir Always sincerely Erskine Neale 14: Bridge St. Blackfriars [Probably Erskine Neale (1804–1883), Anglican clergyman and author, whose work The Life-Book of a Labourer was published by Smith, Elder & Co. in 1839; the letter is addressed to founding partner Alexander Elder (1790-1876). Established heading: Neale, Erskine, ǂd 1804-1883. Probably Sir John Pirie (1781-1851), Lord Mayor of London 1841-1842, who received his baronetcy in 1842. (Prior to that he would have been Mr. John Pirie.) Penn Libraries call number: EC8 N2555 839l Catalog record All images from this book

photo.description: Continuation of letter Envelope Dear Sir The very kind manner in which you were good enough to accede to my request, rendered it doubly incumbent on me to be sure the party for whom I sought your good offices was in every respect deserving. I therefore [Per the envelope, this letter is addressed to Alexander Elder (1790-1876), publisher and co-founder with George Smith (1789-1846) of Smith, Elder, and Co. Per the subsequent signature, it was written by "Erskine Neale" -- probably Erskine Neale (1804–1883), Anglican clergyman and author, whose work The Life-Book of a Labourer was published by Smith, Elder & Co. in 1839.] Established heading: Neale, Erskine, 1804-1883. photo.description: Harry Amyas Leigh Herschel Wade (1873-1959), fourth son of Sir Thomas Francis Wade (1818-1895), the diplomat and Sinologist ("Wade" of the Wade-Giles system of romanization), and his wife Amelia Herschel (1841-1926), daughter of the astronomer John Herschel. Harry was born in Peking (now Beijing); Sir Thomas retired to England in 1888, the same year Harry entered Harrow (along with classmate Winston Churchill!). Harry left Harrow in 1890 and joined the army in 1893, rising to the rank of major by 1910, and was decorated for his service during the Nile Expedition and the Boer War (his eldest brother Alexander was killed in action in the latter conflict). Harry also served in the Great War (on the staff of the 1st Army Corps in France and then as military attaché in Denmark) and was brevetted Lieutenant-Colonel in 1918. In that same year he led a three-member diplomatic mission to Poland and subsequently accompanied Ignacy Paderewski on his return to that country in 1919. Harry Wade appears to have had some talent as a writer and editor, publishing articles on military subjects and editing the Army Review in 1912 and the League of Nations Union in 1919. After leaving the army in 1921, he was an official of the League of Nations and then of the World Court until his retirement in 1937. His obituary in the Times of London notes that he was one of the League's chief "spontaneous translators" [i.e. interpreters]. He was appointed research officer of the United Nations War Crimes Commission in 1944, took part in the Nuremberg trials, and wrote chapters 6 and 7, as well as some of the appendices, of History of the United Nations War Crimes Commission and the Development of the Laws of War (London: HMSO, 1948). He died in 1959. Edward Ernest Bowen (1859-1901) taught at Harrow from 1859 until his death in 1901 and wrote the school song, "Forty Years On." Established heading: Bowen, Edward E. ǂq (Edward Ernest), ǂd 1836-1901. Penn Libraries call number: EC8 Sc862 813r 1874 All images from this book

photo.description: The printer’s device of Mathias Apiarius (ca. 1500-1554) features a bear discovering a bee's nest in the hollow of a tree. At the base of the tree there is a Bible and bees are flying around. The device also features one inscription in Greek and three inscriptions in Latin (Below: "Omnia probate, quod bonum fuerit tenete. 1. Thess. 5.; On the right side: "Quam dulcia faucibus meis eloquia tua, super mel orimeo. Psal. 118. On the left side: "Vrsus insidians & esuriens, princeps impius super populum pauperem. Thre. 3. Prouerb. 28. ) The inscriptions help to explain the meaning of the woodcut: the bear is about to remove a huge mallet hung upon a branch before the hole which contains honey; the mallet will naturally always fall back on him. The device alludes to the name of the printer: Apiarius is the latinized form of the German family name Biener which means "bee master". Established heading: Apiarius, Mathias, approximately 1500-1554 Penn Libraries call number: IC5 R3590 533a 1535 All images from this book
photo.title: Woodcut device of Strasbourg printer Mathias Apiarius, ca. 1500-1554
